register(GUI);
define
drawpath window x=400 y=400 width=400 height=450 fill=gray title="Drawing" closable resize
    intro height=50 pad fill=white rounded
        heading="Draw Path Example" pad=10 label align=center font=title border=off shadow register;
        space height=5;
    jitter pad stride=6 gap=12 depth=2
        wrap pad layers perfColor=darkerGray
           drawPerf perforation;
           body pad=15 fill=paleGray rounded
               arrow drawPath pad border fill=lightGreen>%@40 10 u~ 30 l 30, 40 50 40 -50 l 30 d: 30 T 0 100 R -90;@ 60 20 r 40 u: 30;;

Note: in arrow above, rotate happens after the shift and figuring out how much to shift and the x and y parameters of the shift was a trial and error process. Here is what I figured  # TODO: review

	rotate 90 then first shift x by 100%  # TODO: review
	rotate 180 then first shift both x and y by 100%  # TODO: review
	rotate 270 (or -90) then first shift y by 100%  # TODO: review

The following is taken from the comment describing the path small language defined in Groups.g  # TODO: review

	Drawing grammar - short and sweet. Each command in a drawing path has  # TODO: review
    three components: an operator, an x offset from the current point and  # TODO: review
    optionally, a y offset from the current point. By default, the current  # TODO: review
    point is taken to be the frame origin. The operators that can be used are:  # TODO: review

        %   Length parameters interpreted as % of frame. So an x offset of 50  # TODO: review
            is converted to 50% of the frame width.  # TODO: review
        ~   The current point is taken to be where we currently at and it changes  # TODO: review
            each time a new point is set.  # TODO: review
        @   Move to the new point defined by the following x and y values.  # TODO: review
        :   Close the current path after it is drawn.  # TODO: review
        !   Resets the % and ~ settings to default where offsets are pixel lengths  # TODO: review
            and the current point is the frame origin.  # TODO: review
        a   Draw an arc (do not think this is implemented yet).  # TODO: review
        c   Draw a curve (in addition to the target point, takes two more points as control arguments)  # TODO: review
        d   Direction is down (applies to the y offset).  # TODO: review
        g   Save graphics state  # TODO: review
        I   Invert the current path when drawn.  # TODO: review
        l   Direction is left (applies to the x offset).  # TODO: review
        o	Draw an oval (not implemented yet).  # TODO: review
        r   Direction is right (applies to the x offset).  # TODO: review
        R   Rotate current path by the degrees specified in the x offset.  # TODO: review
        S   Scale current path by amount specified in offsets. If no y offset  # TODO: review
            specified, both x and y are scaled by the x offset amount.  # TODO: review
        T   Shift path by amount specified in offsets.  # TODO: review
        u   Direction is up (applies to y offset).  # TODO: review
        ,	Separates commands that otherwise might be glommed onto the following command.  # TODO: review
        ;	Ends a path, if graphics state saved, restores it.  # TODO: review
        $   Stroke the current path  # TODO: review
        F   Fill the current path  # TODO: review

        The numeric arguments to all commands, except for the rotate command R, are scaled if the % operator is in effect. The arguments for @ resolve to a point. All numeric arguments not associated with the R and @ commands are taken to be lengths, as in how far to move, not defining a point to move to but how far away to move  # TODO: review

